
<p>
    Variables are containers that fall into
    categories that act a certain way: these categories 
    are types.  
</p>
<p>
    Some of the basic types include: 
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <code>String</code>
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>int</code>
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>float</code>
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>char</code>
    </li>
    <li>
        <code>bool</code>
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Creating Variables 
</h2>
<p>
    When a variable is created it must have a type declaration and a name. A value 
    can be assigned later with the assignment <code>=</code> operator.
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-plain">type variableName = value;</code></pre>
<pre><code class="lang-java">int z = 10;
int x;
x = 10;
</code></pre>
<h2>
    Final Variables
</h2>
<p>
    Normally, values of variables can be changed: the <code>final</code> keyword 
    modifies this so it is read-only.
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">final int x = 15;
x = 20;  // Error
</code></pre>

<h2>
    Number Types
</h2>
<p>
    The basic number types include floats and ints, which are decimal and whole numbers. 
    Floats have an <code>f</code> behind them and use a decimal. 
</p>
<pre><code class="lang-java">float myFloatNum = .99f;
int myNum = 1;
</code></pre>

